-- CELL: DEFINER shadow · UNGROUNDED (numeric-literal) receiver · the grounded head HAS a
-- live impl of the shadowed interface.  Clauses S2 + S5.
--
-- This is the cell the corpus was missing, and it is the sharpest one: a numeric literal is
-- `Num a => a`, i.e. UNGROUNDED at inference time, so the routing decision is taken BEFORE
-- the receiver has a head tycon -- and the type is then resolved against a receiver that has
-- SINCE CHANGED.  That "one decision, derived twice, at two different times, over a value
-- that changed in between" is the recurring P0-20 root cause.
--
-- The prelude has `impl Eq Int`, so under the OLD S2 this DISPATCHED: `eq 1 2` was a Bool,
-- `println` rendered it with `Display Int`, `run` E-PANICked and `build` SILENTLY PRINTED 0.
-- P0-20 made the three paths AGREE -- on the dispatch, i.e. on discarding the user's `eq`.
--
-- Under the INVERSION the standalone wins: `eq 1 2` is the user's own function, = 3.
-- groundShadowReceiver is what keeps check/run/build honest here -- it grounds the literal
-- to the standalone's declared domain BEFORE the S2 question is asked, so typecheck and the
-- post-inference route resolver ask it about the SAME head.
eq : Int -> Int -> Int
eq a b = a + b

main =
  println (eq 1 2)
  println (eq 10 20)
